[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.   

With 5 cards in the "other" Major and a 5-card Minor you bid 2\S, Michaels of course. Partner bids 2NT. What do you say next? 

Is it possible that partner wants to play Notrump? Not at all. He hates \Hs and wants you to bid your Minor suit. So you say 3\D and he passes.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "S:A982.J5.A92.Q872 KQ.AKQ83.QJT54.3 J7543.T962.8.KJ4 T6.74.K763.AT965"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "5D"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1C 2NT pass 3D pass 4D pass 5D pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "834754959ca2c7a971cf498d2db8556bb05717ea57c48260d14b70878b1635a1"]
[Category "Competitive Bidding"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "competitive_bidding/michaels_unusual"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown.   

Partner asked you to choose between \Hs and \Ds so you bid 3\D. He then raises you to 4\D.  

If you say to yourself "I only have 7 HCP" then you might pass. But if you say "Partner invited me to bid game, even though I might have no points and only 3 trumps. I'm a lot better than that.", then you will accept the invitation. So you bid 5\D and everybody passes.}

